Exploratory Data Analysis and Model Prediction ¶

Main Question for us: How does the spread and lethality of Covid-19 vary among states of different demographics, and what factors can we attribute to this? How can we use data of current Covid-19 cases and deaths to accurately predict the future?¶

This is a long notebook, so just to make it a bit easier here's a quick summary: We start with cleaning the data, then move onto finding correlations between cases and deaths, then afterwards we analyze states death ratios (deaths/cases) and try to find explanations for why certain states had such large spikes in their death ratios, such as Washington towards the beginning of the pandemic. After this, we move onto predictive models. We start with a couple models that didn't work for predictions (linear regresstion), then move onto the ARIMA model, which the combines autoregressive model and integrated moving average, for forecasting our data.

Cleaning up the Data for Confirmed Cases in US:¶

We start by dropping columns that are not necessary to what we are trying to learn. We also transform the Data Frames so that we can later use the Data Frames for plotting and prediction.

Then Afterwards, we compare and see why they had big spikes in death ratios.

In [658]:
maxStatesRatioUS = caseToDeathRatioUS[["Date", "Washington", "Florida", "Kansas", "South Dakota", "Michigan"]]

As seen in the plot below, Washington, Florida, Kansas, South Dakota and Michigan had the highest spikes in the case to death ratio in the United States. We use this data to try and find corelations.

In [659]:
maxStatesRatioUS.plot(x="Date", figsize = (18, 10))
Out[659]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x13bb9a940>

As you can see in the above plot, Washington, Florida, Kansas, South Dakota and Michigan had the largest spikes in the death to case ratio of coronavirus.

Washington experienced such a large spike because of the community outbreak and the state experienced many of the cases in long-term care facilities during the time period of the spike. Washington was one of the first states to experience a community spread of COVID-19 which is why there spike in the death to case ratio is experienced early on.

Florida experienced such a large spike because of hesitation to create stay at home orders in the state. Some researches attribute this to false negatives during COVID-19 testing. People have also hesitated to seek out care or medical assistance. This rate is said to improve once medical workers got better at identifying patients with cornavirus.

Kansas has had such a large spike in the death to cases ratio because coronavirus testing rates are low per population. The state also has seen large disparities with coronavirus infecting minority groups. Kansas also has the largest racial disparities in COVID-19 death rates. 30% of the coronavirus deaths have been African Americans despite African Americans only making up 5.6% of the states popultion.

South Dakota has experienced a high spike in the death to cases ratio because of spreads in nursing homes. The community outbreak in the state is primarily experienced in these nursing homes that contain the at risk population, people with underlying health conditions and the elderly.

It is argued that Michigan has had such a large spike in death to cases ratio because of when coronavirus hit the state. Michigan doctors were still trying to develop protocalls when they experienced the surge in cases. It is also argued that the coronavirus is deadly in mainly nursing homes and in the African American communities of Michigan. African Americans make up 32% of cases and 41% of the deaths despite only making up 14% of the population of Michigan.

Linear Regression Confirmed Cases to Help Predict Deaths:¶

We use the confirmed cases that day in the United States to predict the deaths that day

This first regression uses the cases per day to predict the deaths per that day

independent_variables = newcompa.drop(columns = ["Death_per_day", "deaths_vs_confirmed", "Date"]).columns
